AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE].

00:42:59.930 --> 00:43:01.540
NAVI RADJOU: Yeah.

00:43:01.540 --> 00:43:03.460
I had the same thought as you.

00:43:03.460 --> 00:43:06.995
In 2006, when I started looking
at it, I first was excited.

00:43:06.995 --> 00:43:09.020
I'm a technologist, so
I thought, that's great.

00:43:09.020 --> 00:43:10.561
And then, yes, I
said, wait a second.

00:43:10.561 --> 00:43:13.230
This is actually creating
more waste or something.

00:43:13.230 --> 00:43:15.170
And this is the good news.

00:43:15.170 --> 00:43:17.900
This is what's going
to happen, next thing.

00:43:17.900 --> 00:43:22.400
The first maker movement
was more about, I would say,

00:43:22.400 --> 00:43:25.100
having fun, and it was
really about technology

00:43:25.100 --> 00:43:26.701
centric movement.

00:43:26.701 --> 00:43:28.200
But you might see--
and it's already

00:43:28.200 --> 00:43:30.970
happening-- the next wave
is a more sustainable maker

00:43:30.970 --> 00:43:32.840
movement, if I can
call it that way.

00:43:32.840 --> 00:43:34.380
So the maker movement
is going to go

00:43:34.380 --> 00:43:36.977
into two dimensions over time.

00:43:36.977 --> 00:43:38.560
The first dimension
is going to become

00:43:38.560 --> 00:43:40.760
what they call social making.

00:43:40.760 --> 00:43:44.005
That means before making was
an individual act, the tinkerer

00:43:44.005 --> 00:43:45.750
alone in their garage.

00:43:45.750 --> 00:43:47.500
Now it's going to
become collaborative,

00:43:47.500 --> 00:43:48.770
so that's the first dimension.

00:43:48.770 --> 00:43:51.129
That's why the tech shops
and things like that.

00:43:51.129 --> 00:43:53.170
That's also where I think--
we can talk offline--

00:43:53.170 --> 00:43:55.461
but where Google can play a
big role, which is building

00:43:55.461 --> 00:43:56.840
the communities around makers.

00:43:56.840 --> 00:43:58.150
That's the first dimension.

00:43:58.150 --> 00:44:00.750
Second dimension is make
it more sustainable.

00:44:00.750 --> 00:44:03.490
So here, what's happening is
that there are companies now

00:44:03.490 --> 00:44:07.740
who are beginning to make
the 3D printers themselves

00:44:07.740 --> 00:44:10.740
using recycled components.

00:44:10.740 --> 00:44:12.920
And then what about
the materials you use?

00:44:12.920 --> 00:44:15.020
Well, there's a whole
cottage industry coming up

00:44:15.020 --> 00:44:18.040
to say, well, what if you use
recycled materials to make

00:44:18.040 --> 00:44:19.026
things?

00:44:19.026 --> 00:44:20.400
And then once you
make the stuff,

00:44:20.400 --> 00:44:22.540
can you use end of life
cycle these products

00:44:22.540 --> 00:44:25.200
you make and bring
it back in the cycle?

00:44:25.200 --> 00:44:28.280
So every principle I
talked about in the area

00:44:28.280 --> 00:44:31.020
of sustainability, you can
apply that to the maker movement

00:44:31.020 --> 00:44:32.290
as well.

00:44:32.290 --> 00:44:36.080
But beyond that, there is
a more convincing argument

00:44:36.080 --> 00:44:38.630
about the making.

00:44:38.630 --> 00:44:41.570
So the 3D printers is
the tip of the iceberg,

00:44:41.570 --> 00:44:43.730
but underneath, there's
a science behind it,

00:44:43.730 --> 00:44:46.230
and this is called
additive manufacturing.

00:44:46.230 --> 00:44:48.240
This is a whole new
way of manufacturing

00:44:48.240 --> 00:44:50.600
which the 3D printers
use, which is essentially

00:44:50.600 --> 00:44:53.910
by adding layers and
layers, which is much more

00:44:53.910 --> 00:44:56.240
sustainable than using the
traditional way of making

00:44:56.240 --> 00:44:58.835
things, where you take a
big chunk of wood or plastic

00:44:58.835 --> 00:45:01.370
or metal and you
chop off anything

00:45:01.370 --> 00:45:03.200
you don't need to
get what you want,

00:45:03.200 --> 00:45:04.864
which creates a lot of waste.

00:45:04.864 --> 00:45:06.280
Here, with additive
manufacturing,

00:45:06.280 --> 00:45:08.560
you don't create that waste.

00:45:08.560 --> 00:45:11.150
Nothing is wasted, essentially,
to the raw materials.

00:45:11.150 --> 00:45:14.040
So that's why the science
underneath the maker movement,

00:45:14.040 --> 00:45:17.390
that is the one that is going
to be a value generating

00:45:17.390 --> 00:45:19.700
area for B2B
companies, whether it's

00:45:19.700 --> 00:45:23.880
Google or GE or Siemens or IBM.

00:45:23.880 --> 00:45:26.250
That's where people
are going to go after.

00:45:26.250 --> 00:45:29.570
And in the process, as
scale kicks in as well,

00:45:29.570 --> 00:45:33.359
it will also make it more
sustainable over time.

00:45:33.359 --> 00:45:34.900
That's a very good
question because I

00:45:34.900 --> 00:45:36.510
had the same doubt
for a long time,

00:45:36.510 --> 00:45:38.051
but now I'm getting
excited because I

00:45:38.051 --> 00:45:41.330
can see how, with
the social aspect

00:45:41.330 --> 00:45:45.920
and the environmental awareness,
this could become actually

00:45:45.920 --> 00:45:48.000
a much more
sustainable alternative

00:45:48.000 --> 00:45:51.860
to traditional
manufacturing over time.

