For example, if I want
to update a case study,

00:47:40.004 --> 00:47:41.920
somebody says, hey, there
is a new case study,

00:47:41.920 --> 00:47:44.461
well, I have to wait six months
before the next release comes

00:47:44.461 --> 00:47:46.050
out.

00:47:46.050 --> 00:47:48.440
If I go with the just
in time writing model,

00:47:48.440 --> 00:47:51.200
I can create a book
where I only have the six

00:47:51.200 --> 00:47:54.580
principles with some
examples, and then I

00:47:54.580 --> 00:47:56.990
can make it evolutionary.

00:47:56.990 --> 00:47:58.740
And then you might
say, well, that's fine,

00:47:58.740 --> 00:48:00.370
but you still have to print it.

00:48:00.370 --> 00:48:02.180
So indeed, yes, there's
a big revolution

00:48:02.180 --> 00:48:05.410
coming in the printing
industry, and the same thing

00:48:05.410 --> 00:48:07.610
like Novartis I talked about.

00:48:07.610 --> 00:48:09.659
There's two companies
creating now-- I

00:48:09.659 --> 00:48:11.200
don't know if Google
is financing it,

00:48:11.200 --> 00:48:14.637
I forgot-- but it's
actually micro printing.

00:48:14.637 --> 00:48:16.470
This is going to be
interesting because this

00:48:16.470 --> 00:48:20.150
is going to allow bookshops that
are dying to actually become

00:48:20.150 --> 00:48:22.661
printing houses.

00:48:22.661 --> 00:48:23.160
Why?

00:48:23.160 --> 00:48:26.510
Because statistics show
that 60%, for example,

00:48:26.510 --> 00:48:30.045
of French people have
memoirs they've already

00:48:30.045 --> 00:48:34.210
written sitting in drawers
they haven't printed yet.

00:48:34.210 --> 00:48:37.150
Now they can just ship the
file to the local bookshop

00:48:37.150 --> 00:48:38.240
and have it printed.

00:48:38.240 --> 00:48:43.430
So this is the device that
completely creates high quality

00:48:43.430 --> 00:48:45.390
book like this with a
nice cover, everything,

00:48:45.390 --> 00:48:47.240
in a small batch.

00:48:47.240 --> 00:48:49.400
So yes, this is
where we are heading.

00:48:49.400 --> 00:48:51.430
It's micro manufacturing.

00:48:51.430 --> 00:48:54.370
And GE, for example, is
moving to the next level

00:48:54.370 --> 00:48:57.800
by partnering with a startup
called Local Garages, which

00:48:57.800 --> 00:49:01.339
makes do it yourself cars.

00:49:01.339 --> 00:49:02.880
Essentially, they
are micro factories

00:49:02.880 --> 00:49:04.960
where you can go and
build your own car

00:49:04.960 --> 00:49:07.540
using open source design.

00:49:07.540 --> 00:49:09.590
And they partner
with Local Garages

00:49:09.590 --> 00:49:11.750
to create what they
call First Build.

00:49:11.750 --> 00:49:14.750
These are micro factories they
want to open around the world

00:49:14.750 --> 00:49:20.840
where consumers can come and
co-create kitchen appliances.

00:49:20.840 --> 00:49:23.100
So essentially, that's
something that GE,

00:49:23.100 --> 00:49:24.970
known for mass
manufacturing, realizes

00:49:24.970 --> 00:49:27.610
that we have to go to the
micro manufacturing model.

00:49:27.610 --> 00:49:29.930
This is going to
absolutely revolutionize

00:49:29.930 --> 00:49:31.890
publication
industry, appliances,

00:49:31.890 --> 00:49:35.260
you name it, even drug industry,
as I said, in the future.

00:49:35.260 --> 00:49:39.169
I think initially, the
motivation will be cost,

00:49:39.169 --> 00:49:40.460
but I think it's not just that.

00:49:40.460 --> 00:49:42.543
I think the bigger factor,
and I haven't mentioned

00:49:42.543 --> 00:49:47.200
that explicitly, is a
desire for consumers

00:49:47.200 --> 00:49:52.720
to create themselves things
and have personalized items.

00:49:52.720 --> 00:49:53.845
This is called IKEA effect.

00:49:53.845 --> 00:49:57.060
If you Google, you'll find
some TED Talks on that.

00:49:57.060 --> 00:49:59.420
70% of consumers
will keep products

00:49:59.420 --> 00:50:01.770
longer if they were involved
in the creation of it.

00:50:04.870 --> 00:50:06.750
This is real,
profound values that

00:50:06.750 --> 00:50:08.587
is going to accelerate
the development

00:50:08.587 --> 00:50:09.545
of micro manufacturing.

00:50:12.880 --> 00:50:14.980
Other thoughts, questions?

00:50:18.745 --> 00:50:19.715
Sure.

00:50:19.715 --> 00:50:22.625
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] any
major companies [INAUDIBLE]?

00:50:22.625 --> 00:50:23.604
Or is it [INAUDIBLE]?

00:50:23.604 --> 00:50:24.270
NAVI RADJOU: No.

00:50:24.270 --> 00:50:25.640
It's actually a good point.

00:50:25.640 --> 00:50:27.560
Actually, far from it.

00:50:27.560 --> 00:50:30.220
Everybody's rebelling
against it because you

00:50:30.220 --> 00:50:33.500
can think about how disruptive
it is for some incumbents.

00:50:33.500 --> 00:50:35.920
But it's an interesting way
to answer your questions,

00:50:35.920 --> 00:50:39.670
not companies rebelling, but
companies' investors rebelling.

00:50:39.670 --> 00:50:44.355
Case in point, Aetna, the health
insurance company, their CEO,

00:50:44.355 --> 00:50:46.105
when I interviewed
him, Mark Bertolini, he

00:50:46.105 --> 00:50:48.260
was saying that the
investors are not

00:50:48.260 --> 00:50:50.870
very happy he's making
the shift because they

00:50:50.870 --> 00:50:54.540
are sitting on a lot of
cash, double digit margins.

00:50:54.540 --> 00:50:59.670
They keep signing more patients
as customers-- life insurance,

00:50:59.670 --> 00:51:00.740
they're selling.

00:51:00.740 --> 00:51:02.320
So why change?

00:51:02.320 --> 00:51:04.706
So he says, well, very
simple, and I'm rephrasing

00:51:04.706 --> 00:51:05.830
what he said from the book.

00:51:05.830 --> 00:51:07.626
He says, well,
because if you keep

00:51:07.626 --> 00:51:09.750
running on the track we
are running, in five years,

00:51:09.750 --> 00:51:11.850
there's no more track left.

00:51:11.850 --> 00:51:14.520
We might as well
forfeit the race.

00:51:14.520 --> 00:51:17.430
So that means that we have to
proactively begin to shift,

00:51:17.430 --> 00:51:20.200
and that's where push back
begins, because whether it's

00:51:20.200 --> 00:51:23.150
senior management in the company
or investors, they're like,

00:51:23.150 --> 00:51:25.180
why do you want to
change the model that

00:51:25.180 --> 00:51:27.100
is working very well?

00:51:27.100 --> 00:51:31.280
So that's why it takes a lot
more guts for senior management

00:51:31.280 --> 00:51:33.660
to say, well, everything's
going well right now,

00:51:33.660 --> 00:51:36.605
but in five years, the drug
industry won't be like this.

00:51:36.605 --> 00:51:39.980
So you have to see something
others don't see and then

00:51:39.980 --> 00:51:42.960
stick to it, and the
next step is to really

00:51:42.960 --> 00:51:45.340
impart that vision to
everybody in the company

00:51:45.340 --> 00:51:49.900
so they believe in what you see
as well, and that takes time.

00:51:49.900 --> 00:51:53.760
So the rebellion will
happen within, of course,

00:51:53.760 --> 00:51:56.300
but also from the
investors as well.

00:51:56.300 --> 00:51:59.555
But I think that if customers
are going to ask for it

00:51:59.555 --> 00:52:01.680
and you're not going to
attract the right employees

00:52:01.680 --> 00:52:05.980
in the future, I think those
are factors strong enough

00:52:05.980 --> 00:52:09.260
to get any company to change.

00:52:09.260 --> 00:52:11.649
At one point, you have
to realize that investors

00:52:11.649 --> 00:52:13.440
are powerful, but
they're not the only ones

00:52:13.440 --> 00:52:15.668
that you listen to.

00:52:15.668 --> 00:52:18.163
AUDIENCE: Why do you
think that attitudes

00:52:18.163 --> 00:52:22.155
about manufacturing [INAUDIBLE]
to decentralize [INAUDIBLE]?

00:52:22.155 --> 00:52:24.467
[INAUDIBLE] increase
[INAUDIBLE]?

00:52:30.551 --> 00:52:32.550
NAVI RADJOU: So additive
manufacturing initially

00:52:32.550 --> 00:52:35.820
will be led by GEs,
Siemens of the world,

00:52:35.820 --> 00:52:37.854
building big factories.

00:52:37.854 --> 00:52:39.520
And what they're
looking at essentially,

00:52:39.520 --> 00:52:41.760
can we take that additive
manufacturing process

00:52:41.760 --> 00:52:46.530
and bring it not to make large
scale production big factories,

00:52:46.530 --> 00:52:49.020
but embed them in
these micro factories

00:52:49.020 --> 00:52:50.500
I talked about earlier.

00:52:50.500 --> 00:52:51.930
So that won't happen overnight.

00:52:51.930 --> 00:52:52.850
So I agree with you.

00:52:52.850 --> 00:52:55.540
It will be a couple of years
before we can transition

00:52:55.540 --> 00:53:00.380
to this micro factory model
of predictive manufacturing,

00:53:00.380 --> 00:53:02.375
but in the short term,
it's to first create

00:53:02.375 --> 00:53:04.500
the proof of concept to
see if it can be done, even

00:53:04.500 --> 00:53:05.500
on a large scale.

00:53:05.500 --> 00:53:07.480
And then eventually,
it will be brought

00:53:07.480 --> 00:53:09.210
to micro factories over time.

00:53:09.210 --> 00:53:13.660
But it will be absolutely
led by large companies who

00:53:13.660 --> 00:53:16.560
have the wherewithal in terms
of science and technology

00:53:16.560 --> 00:53:18.120
development capabilities.

00:53:18.120 --> 00:53:22.190
That's why GE is looking into
it, Siemens is looking at it.

00:53:22.190 --> 00:53:24.660
I can't name some other
companies, but at least seven

00:53:24.660 --> 00:53:27.650
to eight large companies
from the industrial world,

00:53:27.650 --> 00:53:29.870
and also from the
IT technology world,

00:53:29.870 --> 00:53:31.930
are looking at how
to revolutionize

00:53:31.930 --> 00:53:33.140
additive manufacturing.

00:53:33.140 --> 00:53:35.340
So my hope is that as
more large companies

00:53:35.340 --> 00:53:39.650
jump into it, that will create
more innovation to make it much

00:53:39.650 --> 00:53:43.740
more accessible in terms of
bringing it down in scale

00:53:43.740 --> 00:53:47.420
so it can be embedded
in a micro factory.

00:53:47.420 --> 00:53:49.870
And it won't happen, I would
say, in the next five years,

00:53:49.870 --> 00:53:52.579
but over 10, 15
years, it will happen.

